<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1241,1736]" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,461,1241,1267]" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Taxonomic discussion:</emphasis>
—Morphologically, the new species has 4 sepals in staminate flowers (
<figureCitation box="[1285,1438,1242,1268]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1G &amp; H</figureCitation>
), 4 stamens (
<figureCitation box="[267,422,1278,1304]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1G &amp; M</figureCitation>
), connate filaments (
<figureCitation box="[662,755,1278,1304]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1M</figureCitation>
) and horizontally dehisced anthers (
<figureCitation box="[1171,1266,1278,1304]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1M</figureCitation>
), indicating that it is a member of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loureiro" authorityYear="1790" box="[341,495,1314,1340]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Nymphanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[341,495,1314,1340]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Nymphanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The new species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao. A" authorityYear="2022" box="[708,973,1314,1340]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Nymphanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="calcicola">
<emphasis box="[708,973,1314,1340]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Nymphanthus calcicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[1102,1240,1314,1340]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Nymphanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bodinieri">
<emphasis box="[1102,1240,1314,1340]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">N. bodinieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1257,1326,1314,1340]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[247,1352,212,1994]" captionTargetId="figure-30@3.[223,1364,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2 Holotype (E.M. Bodinier 2194; E-00327392) of Nymphanthus bodinieri (Levl.) R.W. Bouman. Female flowers inserted at upper part of branchlets, male flowers inserted at lower part of branchlets." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), a species distributed in 
<collectingRegion box="[299,423,1350,1376]" country="China" name="Chongqing" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Chongqing</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[486,695,1350,1376]" country="China" name="Guizhou" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Guizhou province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[709,776,1350,1376]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">China</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[797,868,1350,1376]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1137,1159]" captionTargetBox="[181,1405,216,1092]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,190,1113]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3 Distribution map of Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao (red circular) and Nymphanthus bodinieri (Lévl.) R.W. Bouman (blue square)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673287" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673287/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao. A" authorityYear="2022" box="[1013,1280,1350,1376]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Nymphanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="calcicola">
<emphasis box="[1013,1280,1350,1376]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Nymphanthus calcicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a dioecious shrub and has cylindrical and twisting branchlets (
<figureCitation box="[710,850,1386,1412]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1B &amp; F</figureCitation>
), leaf blades that are acuminate or acute at apex and broadly cuneate to slightly round at base (
<figureCitation box="[607,723,1422,1448]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1A–F</figureCitation>
), inconspicuous midrib not raised adaxially (
<figureCitation box="[1231,1435,1422,1448]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1A, B, D &amp; F</figureCitation>
), triangular-subulate stipules, female flowers that are 6.5–8.0 mm in diameter (
<figureCitation box="[1002,1101,1458,1484]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1I–J</figureCitation>
) and male flowers 
<quantity box="[1317,1452,1457,1484]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="5.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" unit="mm" value="6.0" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="5.5">5.5–6.5 mm</quantity>
in diameter (
<figureCitation box="[281,405,1494,1520]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1G–H</figureCitation>
), longer pedicels of male flowers that are 
<quantity box="[884,1006,1494,1520]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" unit="mm" value="15.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="10.0">10–20 mm</quantity>
in length (
<figureCitation box="[1130,1251,1494,1520]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1B–C</figureCitation>
), oblate-spherical ovary (
<figureCitation box="[217,306,1530,1556]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1N</figureCitation>
), stigmas that are deeply bifid near to the base (
<figureCitation box="[852,986,1530,1556]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1I &amp; L</figureCitation>
), and obscurely grooved fruits (
<figureCitation box="[1349,1438,1530,1556]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1994,2016]" captionTargetBox="[202,1385,248,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-47@2.[193,1395,242,1966]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Nymphanthus calcicola S.R. Yi &amp; Gang Yao.A‒C. Male plant; D‒F. Female plant; G‒H. Male flower; I‒J. Female flower; K. Fruits; L. Disk glands and pistil of female flower; M. Disk glands and stamens of male flower; N. Ovaries and styles; O. Seeds. (based on the type materal, photoed S. R. Yi)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1K</figureCitation>
). In contrast, the similar species 
<taxonomicName box="[495,633,1566,1592]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Nymphanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bodinieri">
<emphasis box="[495,633,1566,1592]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">N. bodinieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[652,721,1566,1592]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[247,1352,212,1994]" captionTargetId="figure-30@3.[223,1364,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2 Holotype (E.M. Bodinier 2194; E-00327392) of Nymphanthus bodinieri (Levl.) R.W. Bouman. Female flowers inserted at upper part of branchlets, male flowers inserted at lower part of branchlets." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="88">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) is a monoecious shrub and has angled and straight branchlets, leaf blades that ate caudate-acuminate at apex and cuneate at base, visible midrib raised adaxially, triangular stipules, smaller female flowers that are ca. 
<quantity box="[525,590,1638,1664]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
in diameter and male flowers 
<quantity box="[927,1040,1637,1664]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.25" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" unit="mm" value="4.25" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="4.0">4–4.5 mm</quantity>
in diameter, shorter pedicels of male flowers that are not longer than 
<quantity box="[499,581,1674,1700]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
, ovary globose, stigmas that are shallowly bifid to less than 1/2 the length of style, and fruits that are 6-groovded (
<bibRefCitation author="Li, P. T. &amp; Gilbert, M. G." box="[551,760,1710,1736]" pageId="4" pageNumber="88" pagination="180 - 190" refId="ref3274" refString="Li, P. T. &amp; Gilbert, M. G. (2008) Phyllanthus. In: Wu, Z. Y., Raven, P. H. &amp; Hong, D. Y. (Eds.) Flora of China Vol. 11, Science Press, Beijing and Missouri Botanical Garden, St. Louis, 180 - 190." type="book chapter" year="2008">Li &amp; Gilbert 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
